'''Helen Loveday''' (born 1962) is a lecturer in Chinese and Japanese art at the University of Geneva and curator of the Baur Foundation, Museum of Far Eastern Art, Geneva. She has written extensively on Asian art and translated a number of books.
==Early life== Helen Loveday was born in Geneva in 1962. She earned a BA in Chinese studies (1985) and a PhD in Chinese archaeology (1989) from the [[University of Oxford]].<ref name=genev>[https://www.unige.ch/lettres/armus/istar/corpsenseignant/artasiatique/hloveday/ Mme. Helen LOVEDAY.] Université de Genève. Retrieved 12 November 2015.</ref>
==Career== In 2002, Loveday became a lecturer in Asian art at the [[University of Geneva]]<ref name=genev/> where she teaches Chinese and Japanese art. She has been an independent researcher and is also curator of the [[Baur Foundation|Baur Foundation, Museum of Far Eastern Art]], Geneva.<ref>[http://www.odysseypublications.com/aboutUsAuthorsBio.php?personID=000018 Helen Loveday.] [[Odyssey Publications]]. Retrieved 12 November 2015.</ref><ref>[http://fondation-baur.ch/en/contact-us Fondation Baur.] Retrieved 12 November 2015.</ref>
Loveday has written widely on Asian art. Among the books she has translated into English is [[Luce Boulnois]]'s ''La route de la soie-dieux, guerriers et marchands'' (2001) which was published in English in 2004 as ''Silk Road: Monks, warriors & merchants on the Silk Road''.<ref name=boul2004>Boulnois, Luce, with additional material by Bradley Mayhew & Angela Sheng. (2004) ''Silk Road: Monks, warriors & merchants on the Silk Road''. Trans. Helen Loveday. Hong Kong: Odyssey Books & Guides. {{ISBN|9622177212}}</ref>
==Selected publications==
